South Africa’s scandal-plagued power supplier Eskom will appoint a new board and begin the search for a new chief executive at a special meeting in November, Public Enterprises Minister Lynne Brown told lawmakers on Wednesday. Eskom, which is at the centre of allegations of improper dealings in government contracts, has suspended its chief executive and chief financial officer pending disciplinary hearings, both of whom have denied wrongdoing. Read: Eskom CFO Singh to face a disciplinary hearing Many of the allegations are linked to a slew of leaked emails, which Reuters have not independently verified. Read: Auditor-general says Eskom’s wasteful spending balloons